                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Twizlewink wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> This still begs the question - Why do Americans kill each other with guns more then anyone else by a huge margin? </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
As unpopular as this answer might be, it really explains quite a bit.
<br />

<br />
America has more freedoms than any other country, therefore America also has more people that abuse those freedoms more than any other country. We protect the right to be irresponsible. As silly as that may seem, soldiers die to ensure make your own decisisons, even if those decisions are not well thought out. Very few non-Americans can really understand the depth of these freedoms because they have not been this free. Even in countries where a lot of freedoms are protected (England, Canada, etc.) there isn't the same amount of freedom.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Twizlewink wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Japan has a pacifist constitution and is founded on those principles. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Bah, look at the end of WWII. Japan was founded on pacifist ideas because they weren't given a choice. Remember who was allied with Hitler and Nazi Germany? Yeah, Japan. Part of the condition of their surrender was that pacifist stance. 65 years ago they were sailing around the Pacific and marching around Asia slaughtering people. Different generation? Yeah. Founded on Pacifist ideals? No, not without a gun to their heads.
<br />

<br />
Yes, we need education. The problem is that our country is founded on the principle that you also have the right to not be educated, or educated through other means. Freedom is a two edged sword. The government does not have the power to dictate this. And I don't believe it should. But as a result I have to live with people that abuse those freedoms, and I also have to defend myself against people and a government who may try to take those freedoms from me. That is what the 2nd amendment guarantees.
<br />

<br />
Many people ask why we don't have stricter gun laws. Well, because we'd be less free.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Twizlewink wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I can tell you the first thing I intend to do when I become an American citizen (BTW Grats to me, I'm engaged!) is earn my conceal carry licence in Texas. I don't intend to own a gun, but I sure as hell want to know how to handle one and use one effectively if the need arises. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Grats on getting engaged by the way! Good luck to you both! Texas has a lot to offer, but it is definitely different culturally from quite a bit of the rest of the US.
<br />

<br />
Good bit of wisdom! I wish there were more Americans with that attitude. May you never need to use a pistol beyond refreshing your marksmanship occasionally, to confirm that you can hit what you aim at. 
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Twizlewink wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">The benefits do NOT outweigh the consequences. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I disagree but then again, I'm a gun owning American!  <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="icon_smile.gif" border="0" /> 
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Twizlewink wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Compare this system to the Swiss system where every single male is required by law to own an assault rifle and keep it at home </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Yes, but they also don't have the freedom to not own a gun if they don't want one. While this may seem trivial or silly in the context of this discussion, it is just as important to protect the rights of the ones who do not own guns and don't want to. The Swiss are also required to serve a mandatory term in the military, right? That is something that would cause revolution in this country. 
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Twizlewink wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Those who obey the gun laws are the least threatening people, and are not the problem.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I would venture to say it is the same in America as well. The problem isn't the legal gun owners, it's the ones buying the saturday night specials with the serial numbers filed off. My wife who grew up in this town could not recall any child ever being accidentally killed by a gun. And most of the homes here have at least one. Then again most parents teach their children to be careful around them, and send them to gun and hunter safety classes.
<br />

<br />
Yes, America has more accidental firearm related deaths than anyone else. I bet we also have more automobile deaths, alchohol related deaths, and deaths linked to cigarette smoking than any other nation. Heck we probably have more deaths from bungee jumping and skydiving than anyone else too! America is a unique place with unique opportunities. That comes with unique risks and dangers.
<br />

<br />
Maybe it's because we have more people than most other countries. Maybe it's because we are more developed and have more opportunities than many other countries. Maybe it's because we have such an infatuation with statistics, and compile them for every trivial event. Maybe it's because we protect the rights of our people above everything else. I don't have a good answer there. The problem is that there isn't a good solution that doesn't restrict the freedoms and rights of the people.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
