                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">The Constitution is as good as the paper it is written on, or the judge who interprets it.  I think that damage mitigation comment about Enchanters and rocks and paper applies as well to how well the Constitution can stop a FBI sniper's bullet.
<br />

<br />
As for Waco and Ruby Ridge, both episodes demonstrate that yes, the government will come to your home and try to kill you and your family without provocation.  The Second Amendment is supposed to guarantee that the government can't make it easy on itself by making sure that the people can't fight back.  
<br />

<br />
As for what the response to Waco and/or Ruby Ridge ought to have been, I don't know.  Civil war and overthrow of the government is a little harsh.  I have always been a big fan of secession and local government self-determination, but that was tried once in around 1861 and six hundred thousand Americans died in order to "preserve the Union."  I would have liked to see more people held accountable, and fortuantely Randy Weaver's civil suit against the thugs who murdered his wife went well, but there should have been more accountability all the way around, from President Clinton to Janet Reno, on down.
<br />

<br />
The argument for the American revolution, to my mind, was a little weak and rests on some shaky premises of Natural Law.  The best argument was that the colonists had traditional rights as Englishment that the Crown and Parliament were denying them.  A careful reading of the Declaration of Indpendence reveals that it is basically a bill of particulars listing all the particular abuses of the colonists' various rights and privileges.  
<br />

<br />
As for being a modern-day tax protester in the U.S., you'll go to jail.  That's unfortunate, because there is much to commend your position, however, most of us have become accustomed to living under an omnipotent leviathan state that controls every aspect of our lives, and steal 30 or 40 or 50 percent of our income.  (Moreso in Europe than in the U.S. though).  Should you try to overthrow the government?  Sure thing.  I recommend not doing a written constitution in your new government though, especially not if you vest the unreviewable authority to interpret it in an unelected body that is appointed for life!  =)  
<br />

<br />
Ok I think this thread has been derailed in about 5 directions now.  hehehe</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=646635" target="_blank" class="postlink">Saediien Iluvatri</a>
<br />
Coercer/Circle of the Golden Dragon/The Rathe</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
