                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">The Constitution is as good as the paper it is written on, or the judge who interprets it.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">The Second Amendment is supposed to guarantee that the government can't make it easy on itself by making sure that the people can't fight back</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">As for being a modern-day tax protester in the U.S., you'll go to jail</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">especially not if you vest the unreviewable authority to interpret it in an unelected body that is appointed for life!</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Why the four quotes? Not trying to debate any of the them just trying to pick things in your reply (good reply by the way) that I think underline that the way the constitution is interpretated/acted upon/enforced today is very different than the way it was intended when it was written.
<br />

<br />
When it comes to the second ammendment (quote)"the right of the people to keep and bear Arms shall not be infringed" people get very passionate about its literal wording. To paraphrase "I have a constutional right to own a gun and you'll take that away from me over my dead body". Why do people take the meaning of the second ammendment so literally, fight so passionately about it, but not for other ammendments? Something else that has come up in this thread is the patriot act. Does the patriot act violate both the 4th and 6th ammendments? <a href="http://www.law.cornell.edu/constitution/constitution.billofrights.html" target="_blank" class="postlink"> [Ammendments Link]</a> If so why aren't people prepared to die to fight the patriot act? Because it protects them? (People in this thread have argued that taking away someones right to have a gun would protect them). Is it because most/many americans actually own guns but very few are detained in Guantanamo Bay? 
<br />

<br />
I'm not trying to put forward a (pro or anti) (gun or patriot act or goverment) opinion but I do find the debate interesting.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=793464" target="_blank" class="postlink">Satikkine</a>
