                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">One of the most significant difference between the 2nd Amendment and, say, the 4th or 5th Amendments, is that the courts haven't touched the 2nd Amendment.  There is very little interpretation of it, no one so far has been able to, say, get a law overturned because it violates the 2nd Amendment.
<br />

<br />
On the other hand, the 4th a d 5th Amendments for example deal with issue of criminal procedure--what the police and prosecutors can and can't do when they arrest and try to convict you.  A process with which courts are intimately involved and over time a body of law has developed around those amendments about, for exanple, what a "resonable search and seizure" is and isn't.  In my opinion, certain provisions of the Patriot act allow the authorites to supercede some of these procedural protections.  The issue is still shaking out in the courts and we'll see how it ends up.
<br />

<br />
The Second Amendment, however, has an explictly political value.  The courts haven't touched it, really, so it is left to the political process to wrangle with what it means.  I am very comfortable with this, and really prefer courts to stay out of the business of what substantive laws can or can't be passed.  Courts are better at dealing with procedural issues, and when they start overturning laws they run into serious legitimacy problems as far as I am concerned.  I personally find it very slavish to allow 9 unelected lawyer-philosopher-kings decide the ultimate law of the land on every issue they decide to hear.  After all, it takes 3/4ths of the States to amend the Constitution, but the Supreme Court only needs a raw 5-4 majority to do the same thing.   <img src="images/smiles/icon_eek.gif" alt="icon_eek.gif" border="0" /></span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=646635" target="_blank" class="postlink">Saediien Iluvatri</a>
<br />
Coercer/Circle of the Golden Dragon/The Rathe</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
