                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Alot to talk about today, but I'll start here with Oeil's post.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Oeil wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">America has more freedoms than any other country, therefore America also has more people that abuse those freedoms more than any other country. We protect the right to be irresponsible. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
This is a pretty common myth, especially among Americans. Firstly we need to talk about what freedom is. I'd suggest a pretty well rounded definition is "an individuals ability to make decisions which affect their circumstances" The greater the individuals ability, the greater degree of freedom they have. Secondly, we all agree that certain limits are ment to be put on freedom, and that it's the role of the government to enforce those limitations. 
<br />

<br />
For example - you don't have the freedom to murder, steal or rape. Why? Because those things inhibit the freedom of others. Just because the individual doing the murdering or raping has more freedom, it decreases the amount of freedom for others involved. This is why we can jail killers, Enron executives, and rapist in good conscience. The United States does NOT protect your right to be irresponsible or negligent and with good reason since it would violate the very princibles of freedom and liberty it was founded on.
<br />

<br />
On that note, America no longer enjoys the position of being the country with the most freedoms. This was likely true before the World Wars yet in modern times this just isn't the case. I'll compare Americans to Canadians for a few minutes simply to illustrate what I mean. 
<br />

<br />
Consider the "war on drugs" in the USA. In Vancouver possession and use of small amounts of pot are not enforced. It's not an uncommon sight on some of the most popular areas of the city to see people lighting up a joint in street side cafe in front of a police officer who wouldn't even blink and eye. Please note that possession of Marijuana is a criminal offence in Canada - it's just not enforced on that level. Why? Because if I decide to smoke pot I've in no way compromised the personal freedoms of anyone else. 
<br />

<br />
Consider the cronically ill. Cronically ill patients with pre-existing conditions must pay outragously high premiums if they wish to get medical insurance, or they have to pay for it themselves. If someone is unable to receive medical attention because of a condition they've had since birth - this severly limits the choices they can make to govern their own future. Their ability to work, raise a family, and contribute to the world are all severly diminished because of the lack of medical treatment availible to them. In Canada we have a public health care system which means people like my Aunt, who was born with Lupus is able to recieve treatment and thanks to this has been able to have children, contribute enormous amounts to the communties she's lived in (she's been voted citizen of the year in 3 of the 5 municipalities she's lived in, in some she's recieved the honour more then once) all thanks to a system that American's don't have. 
<br />

<br />
Although this doesn't give a complete picture of the two nations - and i'm sure we can argue indefinitely over which country has the "most" freedom but I think it's fair to say that freedoms do require limiitations when they harm others or remove freedoms from other individuals. The dead have no choices - thus no freedom. If someone dies it is the ultimate blow to freedom. 5000+ children dying each year seems to be fundementally opposed to the very idea of freedom you're trying to culture.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Bah, look at the end of WWII. Japan was founded on pacifist ideas because they weren't given a choice. Remember who was allied with Hitler and Nazi Germany? Yeah, Japan. Part of the condition of their surrender was that pacifist stance. 65 years ago they were sailing around the Pacific and marching around Asia slaughtering people. Different generation? Yeah. Founded on Pacifist ideals? No, not without a gun to their heads.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I used Japan to illustrate that changing fundemental legistation has a significant impact on gun related accidents and deaths. Pointing out that the Japanese were extremely violent only 50 some years ago only reninforces that point since it clearly worked. No matter what the motivation for their pacifist stance, it worked. 
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Yes, we need education. The problem is that our country is founded on the principle that you also have the right to not be educated, or educated through other means. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
If you could kindly describe to me the different schools of thought on gun safety and proper gun handling to me I'd love to hear them. As far as I know, gun safety is pretty much a standardized issue and it's something I'm sure the millitary has a great deal of expertise on. Taking the term "education" out of context makes your argument more sounds, unfortunately we're talking about the specifics of gun education. Would you also suggest that driver's licences are inhibiting your freedom? Of course not, because driving safely increases the freedoms of everyone. 
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Many people ask why we don't have stricter gun laws. Well, because we'd be less free.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Again - dead children have no freedom. 
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Twizlewink wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I can tell you the first thing I intend to do when I become an American citizen (BTW Grats to me, I'm engaged!) is earn my conceal carry licence in Texas. I don't intend to own a gun, but I sure as hell want to know how to handle one and use one effectively if the need arises. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Good bit of wisdom! I wish there were more Americans with that attitude. May you never need to use a pistol beyond refreshing your marksmanship occasionally, to confirm that you can hit what you aim at. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I agree, and frankly this is what I would like to see as mandatory. If you want to have a gun, and use a gun, you need to be educated on how to use and handle a gun. It seems obvious, and you wish more people did it, and admit that those that don't are people that you require protection from, yet you don't mandate education but rather suggest we should simply have guns to kill these people instead? I oppose this idea completely. If this is where we agree to disagree, ok, but I wanted to be clear on your stance.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Twizlewink wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">The benefits do NOT outweigh the consequences. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">While this may seem trivial or silly in the context of this discussion, it is just as important to protect the rights of the ones who do not own guns and don't want to. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Aye a bit off topic - but I certainly wouldn't call it silly. Clearly this is an important and emotional issue for alot of people, so I certainly respect and value your opinions and views. After all, I took this thread off topic to begin with too! <img src="images/smiles/icon_wink.gif" alt="icon_wink.gif" border="0" />
<br />

<br />
The Swiss example was simply to illustrate that having alot of guns doesn't increase accidental gun deaths when coupled with education. Clearly the Swiss system wouldn't work outside of Switzerland and I'm sure American's would revolt if such a system were mandated there, as it would in Canada or Britian as well and that's fine. This doesn't disclude the possibility that we can learn from that system and take the key pieces to improve on the American system - primarily the need for gun education. 
<br />

<br />
I would venture to say it is the same in America as well. The problem isn't the legal gun owners, it's the ones buying the saturday night specials with the serial numbers filed off. My wife who grew up in this town could not recall any child ever being accidentally killed by a gun. And most of the homes here have at least one. Then again most parents teach their children to be careful around them, and send them to gun and hunter safety classes.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Yes, America has more accidental firearm related deaths than anyone else. I bet we also have more automobile deaths, alchohol related deaths, and deaths linked to cigarette smoking than any other nation.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
All false. Latvia, Russian Federation, Lithuania and Greece experienced the highest rates of persons killed per population in Automotive accidents, and no one comes close to rivaling the number of cars American's have. Alchohol related deaths have been dropping steadily in the US for the last 20 years or so, in 1996 it was around 32.1 per 100,000 people. Compare that to Finland where 11% of all deaths are related to Alchohol for men, which would assuming no woman drank in Finland (they do) be somewhere around 5,000 deaths per 100,000. China, France, and Spain all have more tabacoo related deaths.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Maybe it's because we have more people than most other countries.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Per Capita measures suggest this isn't the reason, unless you are suggesting that being part of a large country means people want to kill each other more, but I think China disproves that nicely since it's bigger.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Maybe it's because we are more developed and have more opportunities than many other countries.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
If this was the case, Canada, Britian, Japan and a handful of other developed countries would have more gun related deaths, so this is out too.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Maybe it's because we have such an infatuation with statistics, and compile them for every trivial event.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Everyone keeps these stats, it's how we can make these comparisons in the first place.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Maybe it's because we protect the rights of our people above everything else.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
