No. Because it gives the government the ablility to stick the label "terrorist" on whomever it deems worthy, and relieves it of the necessesity to have evidence to prove it. Who exactly is a terrorist. Sure the guys with the knives on the planes taking hostages are terrorists, but what about the grumpy guy that hacks a webpage because he has something he wants to say. Is he a terrorist? Is that where it stops? Is the guy a terrorist that pickets the Whitehouse because he disagrees with the presidents stance on abortion?
<br />

<br />
I know it sounds paranoid, but these are examples of things that have happened in history. A disarmed citizenry can not fight back when you abuse the power that has been trusted to you. If you don't think it happens you haven't been looking at world events.
<br />

<br />
America understood from the beginning that we as humans are not above the corruption that power offers. We are imperfect, and we will be seduced by the ability to force our will on others. We KNOW that power corrupts. We have witnessed that it is a short trip from censorship to tyrrany. We believe that the leaders of this great country will be suceptible to those same desires and downfalls. Therefore we have taken great pains to insure the ability of our citizens to defend themselves against that if it should happen.
